   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Lexical Embeddings\n",
    "### NLP Fundamentals — Session Notebook\n",
    "\n",
    "**Topics covered**\n",
    "1. Why do we need word representations?\n",
    "2. The distributional hypothesis\n",
    "3. Count-based methods: co-occurrence matrices & PMI\n",
    "4. Word2Vec: Skip-gram & CBOW\n",
    "5. GloVe\n",
    "6. FastText\n",
    "7. Evaluating embeddings: similarity & analogies\n",
    "8. Visualising embedding spaces with t-SNE\n",
    "9. Static vs contextual embeddings — a bridge\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "> **Prerequisites:** Python 3.9+, `gensim`, `numpy`, `scikit-learn`, `matplotlib`\n",
    ">\n",
    "> Install: `pip install gensim scikit-learn matplotlib numpy`"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from collections import defaultdict, Counter\n",
    "import warnings\n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams.update({'figure.dpi': 120, 'font.size': 11})\n",
    "print('Imports OK')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 1  Why Do We Need Word Representations?\n",
    "\n",
    "Computers work with numbers, not words.  \n",
    "The simplest way to represent a vocabulary of size *V* is a **one-hot vector**: a vector of length *V* with a single `1` at the position of the word.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "V = {cat, dog, fish, ...}   (V = 10 000)\n",
    "\n",
    "\"cat\"  → [1, 0, 0, 0, ..., 0]\n",
    "\"dog\"  → [0, 1, 0, 0, ..., 0]\n",
    "\"fish\" → [0, 0, 1, 0, ..., 0]\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**Problems with one-hot vectors:**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Problem | Why it matters |\n",
    "|---------|---------------|\n",
    "| All pairs are orthogonal | `similarity(cat, dog) = 0 = similarity(cat, nuclear)` |\n",
    "| Sparse & huge | 10 000-dimensional vectors, mostly zeros |\n",
    "| No semantics | The encoding carries no linguistic information |\n",
    "\n",
    "We need vectors where **similar words have similar representations**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# --- One-hot demo ---\n",
    "vocab = ['cat', 'dog', 'fish', 'car', 'truck']\n",
    "V = len(vocab)\n",
    "word2idx = {w: i for i, w in enumerate(vocab)}\n",
    "\n",
    "def one_hot(word):\n",
    "    v = np.zeros(V)\n",
    "    v[word2idx[word]] = 1\n",
    "    return v\n",
    "\n",
    "def cosine(a, b):\n",
    "    return np.dot(a, b) / (np.linalg.norm(a) * np.linalg.norm(b))\n",
    "\n",
    "cat  = one_hot('cat')\n",
    "dog  = one_hot('dog')\n",
    "car  = one_hot('car')\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'cosine(cat, dog)  = {cosine(cat, dog):.2f}  ← should be HIGH')\n",
    "print(f'cosine(cat, car)  = {cosine(cat, car):.2f}  ← should be LOW')\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('Both are 0.0 — one-hot vectors encode NO similarity information.')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 2  The Distributional Hypothesis\n",
    "\n",
    "> *"You shall know a word by the company it keeps."*  \n",
    "> — J.R. Firth, 1957\n",
    "\n",
    "The core idea: **words that appear in similar contexts have similar meanings.**\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\"The cat sat on the mat.\"\n",
    "\"The dog sat on the mat.\"\n",
    "\"The kitten sat on the rug.\"\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "*cat*, *dog*, and *kitten* share context words (`sat`, `mat`, `the`).  \n",
    "Therefore, we expect them to end up with similar vector representations.\n",
    "\n",
    "All modern static embedding methods (Word2Vec, GloVe, FastText) are implementations of this hypothesis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 3  Count-Based Methods: Co-occurrence Matrices & PMI\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3.1  Co-occurrence matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "Given a corpus and a **context window** of size *k*, count how often each pair of words *(w, c)* co-occurs within that window.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Corpus: \"I like NLP. I like Python. NLP is fun.\"\n",
    "Window size = 1 (one word each side)\n",
    "\n",
    "         I    like   NLP  Python   is   fun\n",
    "I      [ 0     2     0     0      0    0  ]\n",
    "like   [ 2     0     1     1      0    0  ]\n",
    "NLP    [ 0     1     0     0      1    0  ]\n",
    "...\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Each row is then used as a (sparse) word vector."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "corpus = [\n",
    "    ['i', 'like', 'nlp'],\n",
    "    ['i', 'like', 'python'],\n",
    "    ['nlp', 'is', 'fun'],\n",
    "    ['python', 'is', 'fun'],\n",
    "    ['i', 'enjoy', 'nlp'],\n",
    "    ['i', 'enjoy', 'python'],\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "vocab_set = sorted({w for sent in corpus for w in sent})\n",
    "w2i = {w: i for i, w in enumerate(vocab_set)}\n",
    "V = len(vocab_set)\n",
    "WINDOW = 2\n",
    "\n",
    "co_matrix = np.zeros((V, V), dtype=int)\n",
    "\n",
    "for sent in corpus:\n",
    "    for pos, word in enumerate(sent):\n",
    "        left  = max(0, pos - WINDOW)\n",
    "        right = min(len(sent), pos + WINDOW + 1)\n",
    "        for ctx in sent[left:right]:\n",
    "            if ctx != word:\n",
    "                co_matrix[w2i[word], w2i[ctx]] += 1\n",
    "\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "df = pd.DataFrame(co_matrix, index=vocab_set, columns=vocab_set)\n",
    "print('Co-occurrence matrix (window=2):\\n')\n",
    "print(df.to_string())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 3.2  Pointwise Mutual Information (PMI)\n",
    "\n",
    "Raw counts are dominated by frequent words (*is*, *the*).  \n",
    "**PMI** re-weights co-occurrence by how surprising it is:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\text{PMI}(w, c) = \\log_2 \\frac{P(w, c)}{P(w)\\,P(c)}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "- High PMI → the pair co-occurs *more* than chance (informative context)  \n",
    "- PMI = 0  → co-occurrence is exactly what chance predicts  \n",
    "- Low PMI  → the pair co-occurs *less* than chance\n",
    "\n",
    "**Positive PMI (PPMI)** clamps negative values to 0 (negative PMI is unreliable for sparse data):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\text{PPMI}(w, c) = \\max(0,\\ \\text{PMI}(w, c))$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def ppmi_matrix(co):\n",
    "    total = co.sum()\n",
    "    row_sums = co.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)   # P(w)\n",
    "    col_sums = co.sum(axis=0, keepdims=True)   # P(c)\n",
    "    # Avoid division by zero\n",
    "    with np.errstate(divide='ignore', invalid='ignore'):\n",
    "        pmi = np.log2((co * total) / (row_sums * col_sums + 1e-9) + 1e-9)\n",
    "    return np.maximum(pmi, 0)\n",
    "\n",
    "ppmi = ppmi_matrix(co_matrix.astype(float))\n",
    "df_ppmi = pd.DataFrame(ppmi.round(2), index=vocab_set, columns=vocab_set)\n",
    "print('PPMI matrix:\\n')\n",
    "print(df_ppmi.to_string())\n",
    "\n",
    "# Quick similarity check using PPMI rows as word vectors\n",
    "def cos(m, w1, w2):\n",
    "    v1, v2 = m[w2i[w1]], m[w2i[w2]]\n",
    "    denom = np.linalg.norm(v1) * np.linalg.norm(v2)\n",
    "    return float(np.dot(v1, v2) / denom) if denom > 0 else 0.0\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'\\ncosine(\"like\", \"enjoy\") = {cos(ppmi, \"like\", \"enjoy\"):.3f}  ← near-synonyms')\n",
    "print(f'cosine(\"like\", \"is\")    = {cos(ppmi, \"like\", \"is\"):.3f}  ← unrelated')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Limitation of count-based methods:** the vectors have dimensionality *V* (= vocabulary size).  \n",
    "For a realistic corpus *V* ≈ 50 000–500 000 — far too large and sparse for downstream models.\n",
    "\n",
    "We need **dense** low-dimensional vectors. Enter **Word2Vec**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 4  Word2Vec (Mikolov et al., 2013)\n",
    "\n",
    "Word2Vec learns **dense** embeddings of dimension *d* (typically 50–300) by training a shallow neural network on a **prediction task** — not to do the task well, but to obtain useful hidden-layer weights as a side effect.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.1  Two architectures\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n",
    "│  CBOW (Continuous Bag of Words)    Skip-gram            │\n",
    "│                                                         │\n",
    "│  context words → [AVG] → predict  target word → predict │\n",
    "│  target word              context words        │\n",
    "│                                                         │\n",
    "│  \"I ___ cats\"  → \"like\"   \"like\" → [\"I\", \"cats\"]        │\n",
    "│                                                         │\n",
    "│  Faster, good for        Slower, better for             │\n",
    "│  frequent words          rare words                     │\n",
    "└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4.2  Skip-gram intuition (step by step)\n",
    "\n",
    "Given the sentence: `\"The quick brown fox jumps\"`  \n",
    "Window = 2, center word = `\"brown\"`\n",
    "\n",
    "Training pairs generated:\n",
    "```\n",
    "(brown, The)  (brown, quick)  (brown, fox)  (brown, jumps)\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "The network is trained to answer: *"Given 'brown', how likely is each word in the vocabulary to be a neighbor?"*\n",
    "\n",
    "The embedding matrix **W** (shape `V × d`) is what we keep after training. Each row is the embedding of a word."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Illustrate training pair generation for Skip-gram\n",
    "sentence = ['The', 'quick', 'brown', 'fox', 'jumps', 'over', 'the', 'lazy', 'dog']\n",
    "WINDOW = 2\n",
    "\n",
    "pairs = []\n",
    "for pos, center in enumerate(sentence):\n",
    "    for offset in range(-WINDOW, WINDOW + 1):\n",
    "        ctx_pos = pos + offset\n",
    "        if offset == 0 or ctx_pos < 0 or ctx_pos >= len(sentence):\n",
    "            continue\n",
    "        pairs.append((center, sentence[ctx_pos]))\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'Skip-gram training pairs (window={WINDOW}):')\n",
    "print(f'  {pairs[:12]} ...')\n",
    "print(f'  Total pairs: {len(pairs)}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4.3  Negative Sampling\n",
    "\n",
    "Naïvely, the softmax over the full vocabulary (up to 500 000 words) is computed at every step — very slow.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Negative sampling** reframes the task as binary classification:\n",
    "\n",
    "- For each real pair `(center, context)` → label **1** (positive)\n",
    "- Sample *k* random words as fake contexts → label **0** (negatives)\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we only update *k+1* weights per step instead of V. Typical *k* = 5–20.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Positive: (brown, quick)  → 1\n",
    "Negatives: (brown, king)  → 0\n",
    "           (brown, pizza) → 0\n",
    "           (brown, Seoul) → 0\n",
    "```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4.4  Training Word2Vec with Gensim"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from gensim.models import Word2Vec\n",
    "from gensim.utils import simple_preprocess\n",
    "\n",
    "# Small illustrative corpus — the classic 'text8' subset would be better for real use.\n",
    "raw_sentences = [\n",
    "    \"the king rules the kingdom with wisdom and power\",\n",
    "    \"the queen rules the kingdom with wisdom and grace\",\n",
    "    \"the prince is the son of the king and queen\",\n",
    "    \"the princess is the daughter of the king and queen\",\n",
    "    \"the man went to the bank to deposit money\",\n",
    "    \"the woman went to the bank to withdraw money\",\n",
    "    \"the dog barked at the cat in the garden\",\n",
    "    \"the cat slept on the sofa near the dog\",\n",
    "    \"paris is the capital city of france\",\n",
    "    \"berlin is the capital city of germany\",\n",
    "    \"rome is the capital city of italy\",\n",
    "    \"london is the capital city of england\",\n",
    "    \"the scientist discovered a new formula in the laboratory\",\n",
    "    \"the engineer designed a new machine in the factory\",\n",
    "    \"rivers flow into the ocean and the sea\",\n",
    "    \"the sun rises in the east and sets in the west\",\n",
    "    \"the car drives on the road through the city\",\n",
    "    \"the train travels on the rail through the country\",\n",
    "    \"he loved to eat apples and oranges every day\",\n",
    "    \"she loved to eat mangoes and bananas every day\",\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "sentences = [simple_preprocess(s) for s in raw_sentences]\n",
    "\n",
    "# sg=1 → Skip-gram;  sg=0 → CBOW\n",
    "# negative=5 → negative sampling with k=5\n",
    "# window=3, vector_size=50\n",
    "model_sg = Word2Vec(\n",
    "    sentences,\n",
    "    vector_size=50,\n",
    "    window=3,\n",
    "    min_count=1,\n",
    "    sg=1,           # Skip-gram\n",
    "    negative=5,\n",
    "    epochs=300,\n",
    "    seed=42,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "model_cbow = Word2Vec(\n",
    "    sentences,\n",
    "    vector_size=50,\n",
    "    window=3,\n",
    "    min_count=1,\n",
    "    sg=0,           # CBOW\n",
    "    negative=5,\n",
    "    epochs=300,\n",
    "    seed=42,\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print('Models trained.')\n",
    "print(f'Vocabulary size: {len(model_sg.wv)}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# --- Inspect embeddings ---\n",
    "wv = model_sg.wv  # word vectors shortcut\n",
    "\n",
    "print('Embedding of \"king\" (first 10 dims):')\n",
    "print(wv['king'][:10].round(3))\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('Most similar to \"king\":')\n",
    "for word, score in wv.most_similar('king', topn=5):\n",
    "    print(f'  {word:<12} {score:.3f}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# --- Cosine similarity ---\n",
    "pairs_to_check = [\n",
    "    ('king',    'queen'),\n",
    "    ('king',    'prince'),\n",
    "    ('paris',   'berlin'),\n",
    "    ('paris',   'dog'),\n",
    "    ('man',     'woman'),\n",
    "    ('dog',     'cat'),\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f'{\"Pair\":<25} {\"Skip-gram\":>10}  {\"CBOW\":>6}')\n",
    "print('-' * 45)\n",
    "for w1, w2 in pairs_to_check:\n",
    "    sg_sim   = model_sg.wv.similarity(w1, w2)\n",
    "    cbow_sim = model_cbow.wv.similarity(w1, w2)\n",
    "    print(f'{w1} ↔ {w2:<18} {sg_sim:>10.3f}  {cbow_sim:>6.3f}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4.5  Vector Arithmetic & Analogies\n",
    "\n",
    "One of the most famous properties of Word2Vec embeddings:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\vec{\\text{king}} - \\vec{\\text{man}} + \\vec{\\text{woman}} \\approx \\vec{\\text{queen}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "This works because the model learns a **\"royalty\" direction** in embedding space that is roughly consistent across genders."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Analogy: king - man + woman = ?\n",
    "print('Analogy: king - man + woman = ?')\n",
    "result = model_sg.wv.most_similar(\n",
    "    positive=['king', 'woman'],\n",
    "    negative=['man'],\n",
    "    topn=3\n",
    ")\n",
    "for w, s in result:\n",
    "    print(f'  {w:<12} {s:.3f}')\n",
    "\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print('Analogy: paris - france + germany = ?')\n",
    "result2 = model_sg.wv.most_similar(\n",
    "    positive=['paris', 'germany'],\n",
    "    negative=['france'],\n",
    "    topn=3\n",
    ")\n",
    "for w, s in result2:\n",
    "    print(f'  {w:<12} {s:.3f}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 5  GloVe — Global Vectors for Word Representation\n",
    "### (Pennington et al., Stanford, 2014)\n",
    "\n",
    "Word2Vec only looks at **local** context windows.  \n",
    "**GloVe** incorporates **global corpus statistics** (the full co-occurrence matrix) into its objective.\n",
    "\n",
    "### The GloVe objective\n",
    "\n",
    "GloVe minimises:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$J = \\sum_{i,j=1}^{V} f(X_{ij})\\left(\\vec{w}_i \\cdot \\tilde{w}_j + b_i + \\tilde{b}_j - \\log X_{ij}\\right)^2$$\n",
    "\n",
    "| Symbol | Meaning |\n",
    "|--------|--------|\n",
    "| $X_{ij}$ | Co-occurrence count of words $i$ and $j$ |\n",
    "| $\\vec{w}_i, \\tilde{w}_j$ | Target and context embedding vectors |\n",
    "| $b_i, \\tilde{b}_j$ | Bias terms |\n",
    "| $f(X_{ij})$ | Weighting function — down-weights very frequent pairs |\n",
    "\n",
    "### Intuition\n",
    "\n",
    "- The dot product of two word vectors should approximate the **log co-occurrence probability**.\n",
    "- GloVe combines the best of **matrix factorisation** (uses global counts) and **local context** (like Word2Vec).\n",
    "\n",
    "**In practice:** use the pre-trained GloVe vectors from [https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/](https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
