   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## 🔑  Key Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **One-hot vectors** are the starting point — simple, but semantically empty.\n",
    "2. The **distributional hypothesis** is the foundation of all embedding methods.\n",
    "3. **PPMI co-occurrence matrices** are the simplest useful representation but are sparse and high-dimensional.\n",
    "4. **Word2Vec** learns dense 100–300D vectors by training a tiny network on a prediction task.\n",
    "   - Skip-gram: centre → context; better for rare words\n",
    "   - CBOW: context → centre; faster for frequent words\n",
    "   - **Negative sampling** makes training tractable\n",
    "5. **GloVe** combines global co-occurrence statistics with local context, often matching or beating Word2Vec.\n",
    "6. **FastText** extends Word2Vec with character n-grams — handles OOV and morphology.\n",
    "7. All of the above are **static** embeddings. **Contextual** models (ELMo, BERT, GPT) produce different vectors for the same word in different contexts.\n",
    "\n",
